580
00:44:34,790 --> 00:44:35,331
[SPEAKER_06]: Carla Denya.

581
00:44:35,351 --> 00:44:38,755
[SPEAKER_06]: That was terribly dignified, wasn't it?

582
00:44:43,055 --> 00:44:50,503
[SPEAKER_13]: Returning to the question, you don't have to be an economist to see that our economy is not working for the majority of people.

583
00:44:51,545 --> 00:45:02,998
[SPEAKER_13]: Penny is talking about a cost of living crisis, and yes, of course, that's what it is, but you might more accurately describe it as an inequality crisis, because actually some people in this country have been doing very, very well.

584
00:45:03,058 --> 00:45:09,585
[SPEAKER_13]: Some people got substantially wealthier during the pandemic while many of the rest of us struggled.

585
00:45:09,953 --> 00:45:11,435
[SPEAKER_13]: It doesn't have to be like this.

586
00:45:12,396 --> 00:45:20,446
[SPEAKER_13]: We could have well-paid jobs, secure jobs, and a welfare system that really acts as the safety net we need to catch people when they fall.

587
00:45:20,927 --> 00:45:37,969
[SPEAKER_13]: A green economy would create jobs, well-paid jobs distributed all over the country, for example, on a nationwide home insulation program, which would bring down everyone's bills, help with the cost of living in the here and now, give us warmer, more comfortable homes, create hundreds of thousands of green jobs.

588
00:45:37,949 --> 00:45:39,712
[SPEAKER_13]: and support local businesses.

589
00:45:40,693 --> 00:46:05,388
[SPEAKER_13]: And the Greens would provide a real safety net, starting with a £15 minimum wage for all ages, removing the ageist cap on young working adults, an immediate uplift to universal credit, and, my final point, removing the cruel two-child benefit cap that both the Conservatives and Labour's party support, even though it holds 250,000 children down in poverty unnecessarily.

590
00:46:05,408 --> 00:46:06,049
[SPEAKER_13]: Thank you, Paula Denyer.

591
00:46:06,069 --> 00:46:06,690
[SPEAKER_06]: Nigel Farage?

592
00:46:09,050 --> 00:46:12,174
[SPEAKER_08]: I have to say, I think a lot of working people like you feel quite resentful.

593
00:46:12,835 --> 00:46:17,040
[SPEAKER_08]: The harder you work, the more taxes you pay, the less disposable income you have.

594
00:46:17,061 --> 00:46:21,026
[SPEAKER_08]: And yet there are increasingly people opting just not to work.

595
00:46:21,066 --> 00:46:24,210
[SPEAKER_08]: And that number has rocketed over the course of the last few years.

596
00:46:24,230 --> 00:46:25,311
[SPEAKER_08]: So I understand how you feel.

597
00:46:25,672 --> 00:46:27,755
[SPEAKER_08]: Your energy bills are too expensive.

598
00:46:27,775 --> 00:46:29,136
[SPEAKER_08]: They have been for the last 20 years.

599
00:46:29,257 --> 00:46:29,657
[SPEAKER_08]: Why?

600
00:46:29,637 --> 00:46:35,443
[SPEAKER_08]: because we load money, we load tax onto your energy bill to give to wind farm companies.

601
00:46:35,904 --> 00:46:39,567
[SPEAKER_08]: It's kind of the poorer in society giving to the richer in society.

602
00:46:39,908 --> 00:46:42,210
[SPEAKER_08]: Rents, cost of housing, too high.

